          'Outsourcing and deindustrialization: as core countries outsource manufacturing to lower-wage peripheral/semi-peripheral countries, manufacturing jobs in the core decline (deindustrialization) while new industrial zones grow in the periphery — the international division of labor.',
          'Special economic zones (SEZs), free-trade zones, and export processing zones (EPZs) are designated areas in developing countries with relaxed regulations and tax incentives to attract foreign manufacturing investment; create jobs but often with lower wages and weaker labor protections.',
          'Post-Fordism: flexible, just-in-time production methods replacing mass assembly-line manufacturing; enables faster response to market demand, smaller inventories, and geographically dispersed production networks.',
